  "output": "Good picture of the codebase. **No React, no DB queries** — this is a pure Python game engine with Pydantic models. Analysis adjusted accordingly:\n\n---\n\n## Performance Analysis\n\n### 1. Memory Leak — `incoming_orders` grows forever\n\n**`core/models/game.py:36` / `core/engine/order_processor.py:72`**\n\n`incoming_orders` is appended every round but **never consumed or cleared**. After 26 rounds × 3 upstream players = 78 orphaned integers per game in memory, forever if games aren't GC'd.\n\n```python\n# order_processor.py:72 — appends but nobody reads it\nupstream_ps.incoming_orders.append(order_qty)\n```\n\n`place_orders` uses `state.orders_this_round` directly (line 64), not `incoming_orders`. The list is dead weight.\n\n**Fix:** Either remove `incoming_orders` from `PlayerState` entirely, or if it's needed for history, clear it at round end or cap it.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Redundant `IncomingShipment` allocations every round\n\n**`core/engine/order_processor.py:9-12`**\n\nEvery round, `advance_shipments` creates brand-new `IncomingShipment` Pydantic model instances for every in-flight shipment — just to decrement a counter:\n\n```python\nps.incoming_shipments = [\n    IncomingShipment(quantity=s.quantity, arrives_in_rounds=s.arrives_in_rounds - 1)\n    for s in ps.incoming_shipments\n    if s.arrives_in_rounds > 1\n]\n```\n\nWith 4 players × `shipping_delay=2` × 26 rounds = ~208 unnecessary object allocations.\n\n**Fix:** Mutate in place (Pydantic v2 models are mutable by default):\n\n```python\nfor ps in state.players.values():\n    arrived = 0\n    remaining = []\n    for s in ps.incoming_shipments:\n        if s.arrives_in_rounds == 1:\n            arrived += s.quantity\n        else:\n            s.arrives_in_rounds -= 1\n            remaining.append(s)\n    ps.inventory += arrived\n    ps.incoming_shipments = remaining\n```\n\nThis also collapses the two-pass (`sum()` + list comprehension) into one pass.\n\n---\n\n### 3. `round_cost()` duplicated in `accrue_costs`\n\n**`core/models/game.py:41-42` vs `core/engine/order_processor.py:87-90`**\n\n`PlayerState.round_cost()` exists but `accrue_costs` ignores it and reimplements the same formula. If holding/backlog cost logic ever changes, one copy will drift.\n\n```python\n# game.py:41 — exists but unused by engine\ndef round_cost(self) -> float:\n    return self.inventory * HOLDING_COST_PER_UNIT + self.backlog * BACKLOG_COST_PER_UNIT\n\n# order_processor.py:87 — duplicates it\ncost = (\n    ps.inventory * state.config.holding_cost\n    + ps.backlog * state.config.backlog_cost\n)\n```\n\nNote: `round_cost()` uses module-level constants, `accrue_costs` uses `state.config` — so they'd diverge on non-default configs.\n\n**Fix:** Use `state.config` in `round_cost()` or pass config in, then call it from `accrue_costs`:\n\n```python\ndef accrue_costs(state: GameState) -> GameState:\n    cfg = state.config\n    for ps in state.players.values():\n        ps.cumulative_cost += ps.inventory * cfg.holding_cost + ps.backlog * cfg.backlog_cost\n    return state\n```\n\nAnd either remove `round_cost()` or fix it to use `GameConfig`.\n\n---\n\n### 4. `is_round_complete` allocates set every call\n\n**`core/models/game.py:55-57`**\n\nCalled potentially on every WebSocket message or order submission:\n\n```python\ndef is_round_complete(self) -> bool:\n    active_roles = {role for role, ps in self.players.items() if not ps.is_ai}\n    return active_roles.issubset(self.orders_this_round.keys())\n```\n\nSet comprehension + `issubset` on every check. For 4 players it's negligible now, but the active roles set is derived from a static property (AI assignment doesn't change mid-game).\n\n**Fix:** Cache `active_human_roles` on `GameState` at creation time:\n\n```python\n# In GameState or computed once in create_game\nactive_human_roles: frozenset[PlayerRole] = Field(default_factory=frozenset)\n\ndef is_round_complete(self) -> bool:\n    return self.active_human_roles.issubset(self.orders_this_round)\n```\n\n---\n\n### 5. Caching opportunity — WebSocket visible state\n\n**`core/engine/game_engine.py:83-96`**\n\n`get_visible_state` calls `s.model_dump()` on every shipment, every time any player polls. With WebSockets this will be called frequently.\n\n**Fix:** Once FastAPI is wired up, cache `get_visible_state` output per `(game_id, role, current_round)` — invalidate on `process_round`. Redis is already in the stack for exactly this.\n\n---\n\n### Summary table\n\n| Issue | File | Impact | Effort |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `incoming_orders` memory leak | `order_processor.py:72` | Low now, scales with sessions | Low — delete the field or clear it |\n| `IncomingShipment` churn | `order_processor.py:9-12` | Medium — O(pipeline×players×rounds) allocs | Low — mutate in place |\n| `round_cost()` drift risk | `game.py:41` vs `order_processor.py:87` | Correctness risk | Low — unify |\n| `is_round_complete` set alloc | `game.py:55` | Negligible now | Low — precompute |\n| WebSocket state caching | `game_engine.py:83` | High at scale | Medium — needs Redis integration |\n\nNo React (SvelteKit only, no frontend yet) and no DB (pure in-memory) — those categories don't apply yet. Add DB-layer analysis once SQLAlchemy/asyncpg queries land.\n",
